Actions against Japanese Ultra-Right Forces' Moves to Exterminate Koreans Called for 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, February 11 (KCNA) -- Yun Ki Jin, chairman of the South Headquarters of the National Alliance of Youth and Students for the Country's Reunification reportedly published an appeal on Feb. 6 calling on the Koreans to turn out in the actions to bring the Japanese reactionaries' suppression of the General Association of Korean Residents in Japan (Chongryon) and Koreans in Japan to an end. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The appeal said: Koreans are falling victim to the crackdown by the Japanese ultra-right forces in the June 15 era when the movement for placing the nation above anything else and defending the nation and the nation-first spirit are running high. It is a vital issue of the nation which brooks not a moment's delay to put an end to this alarming development. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Japan should not be allowed to trifle with the destiny of the Korean nation any longer as it had bled the Koreans white for more than 40 years after depriving Korea of its sovereignty. All the members of the Korean nation are called upon to turn out in the struggle to put an end to the suppression of Chongryon and Koreans in Japan in the spirit of taking revenge upon it. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The appeal urged the people from all walks of life to unite as one on March 1 to deal a heavy blow at Japan and put pressure on it to stop at once its suppression of Koreans in Japan. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It called for smashing the Japanese ultra-right forces' moves for exterminating the Korean nation holding high the banner of attaching importance to the nation.

Suppression of Chongryon and Koreans in Japan Flailed 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Pyongyang, February 10 (KCNA) -- The Japanese reactionaries again perpetrated fascist suppression of the General Association of Korean Residents in Japan (Chongryon) and their commercial organizations recently. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 On Feb. 6 the Hyogo Prefectural Police Agency searched the Hyogo Prefectural Headquarters and the Hyogo Prefectural Commercial Association of Chongryon in the wake of the similar actions on Dec. 5 last year and on Jan. 10 this year. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 From early that morning the police authorities mobilized more than 250 armed policemen for cracking down upon Korean workers in commerce on the charge of violation of the "law on taxation." Not content with this, they drove five armored cars to cutting off the traffic around the headquarters before searching its hall and the house of the chief of the Business Office of the association. Then they walked away the chief of the office. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 At night on Feb. 4 the Hokkaido police authorities arrested the deputy managing director of the Sapporo Commercial Association on charges of the violation of the above-said law and Korean businessman Kim Hwa Su and his wife and others on charges of the violation of the "law on income tax." &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 On Feb. 5 the Sapporo District Prosecutor's Office and the Hokkaido Police Agency searched the Hokkaido Headquarters of Chongryon, its Sapporo branch and offices of the Korean Youth League in Japan and the Korean Democratic Women's Union in Japan inside the hall of the headquarters, the Hokkaido Commercial Association, the Sapporo Commercial Association and houses of the deputy managing director of the association and of Kim Hwa Su and his son for 12 hours and a half, claiming that they are suspicious of violating the "law on taxation" and the "law on income tax." They ransacked Kim's house, groundlessly asserting that "some of the money earned by a shop run by him was likely to be wired to the north." &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Greatly enraged by this, officials of the Hyogo Headquarters of Chongryon and Koreans in the prefecture strongly protested against the police on Feb. 6. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Meanwhile, members of the Korean Youth League in Japan and Koreans in Hyogo Prefecture held a rally in protest against the fascist suppression in front of the prefectural building before taking to the streets. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The protesters included officials of Chongryon and Koreans in Kinki Region including Osaka and Kyoto. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 On Feb. 6 the Hokkaido Headquarters of Chongryon called a press conference at which it denounced the hideous suppression of Chongryon and Koreans in Japan by the Japanese authorities.
